abstract: WASHINGTON, Dec. 6.--The principal action of the Senate to-day was the fixing of Tuesday next as the day for the consideration of the Silver bill. It will be brought up at that time as a special order, and will hold its place before the Senate until finally disposed of. The discussion had no reference to the merits of the bill, and was very brief, relating merely to the time which should be set for consideration.

abstract: LONDON, Dec. 12--The estimates of the number of Turks captured at Plevna telegraphed from St. Petersburg last night--10,000, exclusive of 20,000 sick and wounded-- are worthless, as there are no better means of estimating the number there than here. The Vienna correspondent of the Times, after a careful survey of the operations about Plevna since July, with the various losses and reinforcements, arrives at the conclusion that Osman Pasha surrendered less than 30,000 men altogether.

abstract: The work of searching for bodies in the ruins of Greenfield  Son's candy factory, in Barelaystreet, was continued all day yesterday. At 11:40 one of the workmen uncovered a human hand and the arm, completely calcined. Next a single-barreled pistol and a coupl of watch-chains were brought to light, and then the remainder of the body. It was burned beyond recognition, and only a portion of the clothing remained. One foot was entirely gone.

abstract: The Kings County Board of Supervisors held their last meeting yesterday for the present year.  A communication was received from the Supervisor at Large vetoing the resolution passed by the last meeting of the board providing for the erection, at a cost of $120,000, of a wing to the Couuty Jail. The reason set forth in the veto was that the addition was not urgently needed.
